00:00:00.900 --> 00:00:02.900
Voiceover:Rahul's two favorite foods

00:00:02.900 --> 00:00:04.533
are bagels and pizza.

00:00:04.967 --> 00:00:08.633
Let A represent the event that he eats

00:00:08.633 --> 00:00:13.233
a bagel for breakfast and let B represent

00:00:13.233 --> 00:00:15.400
the event that he eats pizza for lunch.

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:16.666
Fair enough.

00:00:16.900 --> 00:00:19.633
On a randomly selected
day, the probability

00:00:19.633 --> 00:00:22.566
that Rahul will eat a bagel for breakfast,

00:00:22.566 --> 00:00:24.767
probability of A, is .6.

00:00:24.767 --> 00:00:25.933
Let me write that down.

00:00:25.968 --> 00:00:28.966
So the probability that he eats a bagel

00:00:28.966 --> 00:00:32.333
for breakfast is 0.6.

00:00:32.833 --> 00:00:35.766
The probability that he
will eat a pizza for lunch,

00:00:35.766 --> 00:00:37.933
probability of event B ...

00:00:38.433 --> 00:00:40.233
So the probability of ...

00:00:40.233 --> 00:00:41.666
Let me do that in that red color.

00:00:42.330 --> 00:00:45.166
The probability of event B, that he eats

00:00:45.166 --> 00:00:48.733
a pizza for lunch, is 0.5.

00:00:49.433 --> 00:00:52.340
And the conditional
probability, that he eats

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:55.766
a bagel for breakfast given that he eats

00:00:55.766 --> 00:00:58.500
a pizza for lunch, so
probability of event A

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.500
happening, that he eats
a bagel for breakfast,

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:03.300
given that he's had a pizza for lunch

00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:05.933
is equal to 0.7, which is interesting.

00:01:06.166 --> 00:01:07.330
So let me write this down.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:15.100
The probability of A given,
given that B is true.

00:01:15.100 --> 00:01:22.000
Given B, is not 0.6, it's equal to 0.7.

00:01:22.166 --> 00:01:24.433
And because these two
things are not the same,

00:01:24.433 --> 00:01:27.330
because the probability of A by itself

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:28.833
is different than the probability of A

00:01:28.833 --> 00:01:32.701
given that B is true, this tells us that

00:01:32.701 --> 00:01:35.133
these two events are not independent.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:37.766
That we're dealing with
dependent probability.

00:01:37.766 --> 00:01:38.933
This shows us.

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:42.330
The fact that B being true has changed

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:45.566
the probability of A
being true, this tells us

00:01:45.566 --> 00:01:47.667
that A and B are dependent.

00:01:47.968 --> 00:01:49.933
Dependent.

00:01:50.566 --> 00:01:51.900
And so when we start thinking ...

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:53.433
Well actually let's just, before I start

00:01:53.433 --> 00:01:55.833
going on my little soapbox
about dependent events,

00:01:55.833 --> 00:01:57.166
let's just think about what they actually

00:01:57.166 --> 00:01:58.400
want us to figure out.

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:02.566
So the probability, the probability of A

00:02:02.566 --> 00:02:04.566
given B is equal to 0.7, that's what

00:02:04.566 --> 00:02:05.867
we wrote right over here.

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:08.350
Based on this information,
what is the probability

00:02:08.350 --> 00:02:10.133
of B given A?

00:02:10.633 --> 00:02:12.433
So they want us to figure
out the probability

00:02:12.433 --> 00:02:14.933
of B given ...

00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:18.533
Probability of B given A.

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:21.300
That's what they want us to figure out.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:22.566
The conditional probability that Rahul

00:02:22.566 --> 00:02:25.167
eats pizza for lunch, given that he eats

00:02:25.167 --> 00:02:28.300
a bagel for breakfast, rounded to the

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:29.800
nearest hundredth.

00:02:30.633 --> 00:02:31.966
So how would we think about this?

